      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Believing that presidential nominations are controlled by party leaders and not average voters, 75 percent of Americans advocate a national primary (news article, May 18).</p>
        <p>For the last 30 years we have tinkered with the presidential nomination system in a misguided effort to make it more ''democratic.'' Replacing deliberative party conventions with popular primaries has harmed political parties, the true engines of democracy, by encouraging a candidate-centered politics that emphasizes money, media and ''momentum,'' which candidates acquire by beating up more on fellow party rivals than on the opposition.</p>
        <p>A democratic electoral process owes the people the final say; it does not entitle them to the first say.</p>
        <p>GERARD J. FITZPATRICK  Collegeville, Pa., May 18, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of politics at Ursinus College.</p>
      </block>
